refentry.refsect1:
&reftitle.description;
boolimagejpeg GdImageimage resourcestringnullfile&null; intquality-1
imagejpeg creates a JPEG file from the given image.

  &reftitle.parameters;



    &gd.image.description;

     file


&gd.image.path;



     quality



       quality is optional, and ranges from 0 (worst
       quality, smaller file) to 100 (best quality, biggest file). The 
       default (-1) uses the default IJG quality value (about 75).

&reftitle.changelog;





    &Version;
    &Description;





    8.4.0

     Now throws a ValueError if quality is invalid.


   &gd.changelog.image-param;

  &reftitle.examples;



    Outputting a JPEG image to the browser


<?php
// Create a blank image and add some text
$im = imagecreatetruecolor(120, 20);
$text_color = imagecolorallocate($im, 233, 14, 91);
imagestring($im, 1, 5, 5,  'A Simple Text String', $text_color);

// Set the content type header - in this case image/jpeg
header('Content-Type: image/jpeg');

// Output the image
imagejpeg($im);
?>


    &example.outputs.similar;

     Output of example : Outputting a JPEG image









    Saving a JPEG image to a file


<?php
// Create a blank image and add some text
$im = imagecreatetruecolor(120, 20);
$text_color = imagecolorallocate($im, 233, 14, 91);
imagestring($im, 1, 5, 5,  'A Simple Text String', $text_color);

// Save the image as 'simpletext.jpg'
imagejpeg($im, 'simpletext.jpg');
?>







    Outputting the image at 75% quality to the browser


<?php
// Create a blank image and add some text
$im = imagecreatetruecolor(120, 20);
$text_color = imagecolorallocate($im, 233, 14, 91);
imagestring($im, 1, 5, 5,  'A Simple Text String', $text_color);

// Set the content type header - in this case image/jpeg
header('Content-Type: image/jpeg');

// Skip the file parameter using NULL, then set the quality to 75%
imagejpeg($im, NULL, 75);
?>

&reftitle.notes;



  If you want to output Progressive JPEGs, you need to set interlacing
  on with imageinterlace.
